## Findings

Given these methods run on **every user-facing string** in your CMS, all code here is hot-path.

---

#### 1. LINQ chain in FromPascalCase (5 allocations per call) 🔴
**Impact:** Every `Humanize()` of a PascalCase string allocates: `Cast<>` enumerator, `Select` enumerator, delegate closure, intermediate `IEnumerable<string>`, and the `string.Join` internal array. Hundreds of calls per page.
**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L86-98`
**Fix:** Replace with a `foreach` loop over `MatchCollection` (which is directly enumerable in .NET 7+) and build the result with a `ValueStringBuilder` or `Span<char>` buffer.

```csharp
internal static string FromPascalCase(string input)
{
    var matches = PascalCaseWordPartsRegex().Matches(input);
    if (matches.Count == 0)
        return input;

    // Estimate: each word + space separator
    var sb = new StringBuilder(input.Length + matches.Count);
    for (int i = 0; i < matches.Count; i++)
    {
        if (i > 0) sb.Append(' ');
        var value = matches[i].Value;
        bool allUpper = true;
        foreach (char c in value)
        {
            if (!char.IsUpper(c)) { allUpper = false; break; }
        }
        if (allUpper &&
            (value.Length > 1 || (matches[i].Index > 0 && input[matches[i].Index - 1] == ' ') || value == "I"))
            sb.Append(value);
        else
            sb.Append(value.ToLowerInvariant());
    }

    string result = sb.ToString();
    // Check if all-upper acronym string needs lowering
    bool needsLower = result.Contains(' ');
    if (needsLower)
    {
        foreach (char c in result)
        {
            if (c != ' ' && !char.IsUpper(c)) { needsLower = false; break; }
        }
    }
    if (needsLower)
        result = result.ToLowerInvariant();

    return result.Length > 0
        ? string.Concat(char.ToUpperInvariant(result[0]).ToString().AsSpan(), result.AsSpan(1))
        : result;
}
```

---

#### 2. Dehumanize→Humanize→Pascalize double-processing loop (N×6+ allocations) 🔴
**Impact:** `Dehumanize` (L171) calls `word.Humanize().Pascalize()` per word. `Pascalize` (L187) internally calls `Humanize()` **again**, then `Transform()`, then `.Replace(" ", "")`. Each word triggers 6+ allocations and redundant re-humanization.
**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L166-171, L187`
**Fix:** `Pascalize` should capitalize the first char directly without re-humanizing. `Dehumanize` should use `StringBuilder` instead of LINQ `Select`.

```csharp
public static string Pascalize(this string input)
{
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(input)) return input;
    // Split into words, title-case each, join without spaces
    var words = input.Humanize().Split(' ', StringSplitOptions.RemoveEmptyEntries);
    var sb = new StringBuilder(input.Length);
    var textInfo = System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture.TextInfo;
    foreach (var word in words)
        sb.Append(textInfo.ToTitleCase(word));
    return sb.ToString();
}

public static string Dehumanize(this string input)
{
    var words = input.Split(' ', StringSplitOptions.RemoveEmptyEntries);
    if (words.Length == 0) return input;
    var sb = new StringBuilder(input.Length);
    var textInfo = System.Globalization.CultureInfo.CurrentCulture.TextInfo;
    foreach (var word in words)
        sb.Append(textInfo.ToTitleCase(word));
    return sb.ToString();
}
```

